Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

Thanks for review Victor fixed import issue. To respond to your question about ibm_db_sa, yes I'm sure that is the way to get sqlalchemy connected with DB2, this is how I test as well. About your concern changing migration scripts, I agree with this statement as long as there is no failures during the migration run. At the moment I just don't see another way, these scripts were never tested with DB2 as backend before, to be honest I'm amazed everything worked after these changes, sqlalchemy handles almost everything well.

Patch Set 8: Do not merge

I think the code here looks okay. However, I'm concerned, are we supporting db2? Is there some gate-testing going into place?

The fact that this is changing migrations makes me feel a bit odd as well.

Maybe there is a larger openstack discussion that has happened around DB2 adoption that I have just missed out on. I'd love to hear more about that.

Patch Set 8:

Thanks for review Mark. Here is the DB2Enablement wiki page:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/DB2Enablement. Keystone and Ceilometer already have support. Yes IBM will provide the test infrastructure as explained in the wiki, but in my humble opinion it is up to each project to accept the migration changes needed prior to DB2 being added as a gate. The ibm_db_sa is already a supported sqlalchemy dialect. There are minors changes still need as you can see in this patch set already under review: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/55572/ I think the DB2 support wheels are turning and IBM is comited to provide the needed resource to make sure is adequately tested to avoid regressions. Let me know if you have any other specific questions. Here is also a mailing list discussion on CI testing
